   <abstract >The purpose of this dissertation is to provide a conductor's analysis of a specific set of repertoire by Paul J. Christiansen. The selected works were limited to Paul J.'s arrangements of pre-existing musical material. In-depth analysis was limited to works in print and available for purchase still today. The author seeks to facilitate informed performance of these works and provide a general resource for conductors who have an interest in performing the music of Paul J. Christiansen.The study includes a short biography of Paul J.'s life and career, providing a brief historical context for this man's work. It also includes a short history of the development of the Concordia College choral department, namely the Concordia Choir and Concordia Christmas concert, for which Paul J. was synonymous for nearly five decades. An annotated catalog of Paul J.'s many choral arrangements is provided. Brief information about the key, meter, tempo, origin, performance length, date of publication, publisher, and voicing is provided. The study concludes with an analysis of two subsets of arrangements of Paul J. Christiansen: Christmas carols and folk tunes. These subsets of arrangements include the vast majority of Paul J.'s works that continue to be frequently performed and are available for purchase. For each piece, a general overview is provided, followed by a form and suggested performance notes.</abstract>
